Q FEVER - UK (WALES)
******************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>


Date: Sat, 26 Oct 2002 17:02:16 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: The Guardian [edited]
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,3604,819594,00.html>


Fever outbreak kept quiet to avoid panic
------------------------------------
Public health officials admitted they had not publicized an outbreak of a
rare but potentially debilitating and fatal disease when it was at its
height because of fears that the local population would panic. Up to 86
people are thought to have caught Q fever in an outbreak that is puzzling
public health officials, although it was restricted to one factory
manufacturing cardboard in Newport, south Wales.

Workers and subcontractors started falling ill in July 2002 and the
illnesses peaked in August. Some needed brief hospital treatment. Most are
said to be fully recovered and back at work, but some are still suffering
long-term weakness associated with the disease, which usually affects
farmers or abattoir staff. This time no link has been established with animals.

A total of 59 people have been confirmed as having had the disease, which
can lead in a small minority of cases to lung damage or even death. A
further 13 are considered probable victims of the disease, with 14 possible
cases.

The scale of the outbreak came to light yesterday when the public health
laboratory service for England and Wales (PHLS) told doctors to contact
officials if they saw patients with pneumonia-like symptoms who had
recently been to Newport.

The local evening paper had a news item on 21 Sep 2002 suggesting more than
40 people might have been taken ill, but a spokesman for Gwent health
authority said yesterday it had decided not to make a general announcement
about the outbreak "because it was not spreading beyond the confines of the
factory". People in the company concerned had been kept fully informed, he
said. There was concern that publicity would cause a panic.

No new cases have been identified in Newport in recent weeks.
Investigations into the cause are said to be continuing. In all 214 people
who worked at the factory were interviewed and tested.

Only around 70 cases of Q fever are usually identified each year in England
and Wales. Last year that figure fell to 47, probably because of the foot
and mouth cull, although 3 of those were soldiers disposing of carcasses.

[Byline: James Meikle]

